","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Wishart  . This surname is very rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Wisehart","meanings":["Probably an Americanized form of German <b>Weisshardt</b>, from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wīs</i> ‘wise’ + <i>hart</i> ‘strong, hard’.","Perhaps an altered form of Scottish   Wishart  ."]}]},{"name":"Andrew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the Greek name <i>Andreas</i>, a short form of any of various compound names derived from <i>andr-</i> ‘man, warrior’. In the New Testament this is the name of the first disciple to be called by Jesus. After the Resurrection,  St Andrew  preached in Asia Minor and Greece. He is traditionally believed to have been crucified at Patras in Achaia. He was one of the most popular saints of the Middle Ages and was adopted as the patron of Scotland, Russia, and Greece. It has long been among the most popular boys' names in the English-speaking world, especially in Scotland. Its popularity in England was further enhanced by its use as a British royal name for  Prince Andrew  (  b. 1960 ), the Duke of York."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Andrew Wishart was born about 1240, in Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Wishart III, was 36 and his mother, Lady Johanna de Predelathe, was 34. He had at least 2 sons. He died in November 1308, in his hometown, at the age of 69."},"et":{"about 1240–November 1308":"umbes 1240–november 1308","1240–1308":"1240–1308","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1270–Male":"1270–Surnud","1206–Male":"1206–Surnud","1208–Female":"1208–Surnud","1206":"1206","1240":"1240","November 1308":"november 1308","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1308":"1308","about 1240":"umbes 1240","1208":"1208","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1240–November 1308":"noin 1240–marraskuu 1308","1240–1308":"1240–1308","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1270–Male":"1270–Kuollut","1206–M